{
  "esm": "0.6.0",
  "metadata": {
    "name": "edge_enumeration_area_eff",
    "description": "M3 value-invention END-TO-END worked example (RFC semiring-faq-unified-ir §7.3 / §5.2 / §5.5; bead ess-my4.3.10): the complete §7.3 chain in one document — the operation einsum cannot do, replacing imperative unstructured-mesh Julia. (1) `edge_set` is the index-set-producing aggregate (semiring bool_and_or, distinct:true) that enumerates the unique undirected edges from the face->vertex connectivity: it iterates each face `f` and the pairs (a,b) of its vertices (ranges drawn {from} the ragged `face_vertices` set), keeps a<b via `filter` (each undirected edge once), mints a canonical Skolem key skolem(edge,a,b) per pair, and the `true` body marks existence — so distinct dedups to the content-addressed edge set, in the §5.7 sorted order. (2) `edges` is exposed as a kind:\"derived\" index set via from_faq:\"edge_set\". (3) `edge_dense_id` ranks it to dense ids for the array backend. (4) `edges_of_cell` is the ragged INVERSION join (§5.2): the edges incident on each cell, bound to its offsets (n_edges_on_cell) + values (edges_on_cell) factors. (5) the downstream geometric FAQ `area_eff[i]` is an ordinary sum_product over edges_of_cell(i): the DUO effective area 1/4 * Sum_k dc[e]*dv[e] where e=edges_on_cell(i,k), dc the cell-center distance across the edge and dv the edge length — consuming `edges` as a PRIMITIVE index set, no imperative edge loop. This is a STRUCTURAL fixture: it validates against the schema (the additive M3 deltas — semiring, distinct, key, filter, {from}/of ranges, derived/ragged index sets) and is the documentation-grade embodiment of the whole chain. Its two halves are verified across Julia/Rust/Python by the OTHER conformance fixtures: the value-invention half (enumerate -> skolem/distinct -> rank) is pinned byte-identically by the determinism `edge_enumeration` golden and the cadence `pure_topology` golden (CONST-fold; and `discrete_remesh_topology` for the DISCRETE remesh path), and the downstream sum_product FAQ over the materialized `edges` set evaluates numerically in all three bindings via `area_eff_edge_faq.esm`. The mesh here is the canonical 2-triangle mesh (faces {1,2,3},{2,3,4}; 5 edges) used by all of those goldens.",
    "authors": [
      "EarthSciSerialization/polecats/gastown.nux"
    ],
    "tags": [
      "aggregate",
      "skolem",
      "distinct",
      "rank",
      "ragged",
      "edges-of-cell",
      "value-invention",
      "geometric-faq",
      "end-to-end",
      "conformance",
      "schema",
      "ess-my4.3.10"
    ]
  },
  "models": {
    "EdgeEnumerationAreaEff": {
      "index_sets": {
        "faces": { "kind": "interval", "size": 2 },
        "cells": { "kind": "interval", "size": 2 },
        "face_vertices": {
          "kind": "ragged",
          "of": ["faces"],
          "offsets": "n_verts_on_face",
          "values": "verts_on_face"
        },
        "edges": { "kind": "derived", "from_faq": "edge_set" },
        "edges_of_cell": {
          "kind": "ragged",
          "of": ["cells"],
          "offsets": "n_edges_on_cell",
          "values": "edges_on_cell"
        }
      },
      "variables": {
        "n_verts_on_face": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "shape": ["faces"],
          "description": "Valence of each face (vertices per face) — the ragged `face_vertices` offsets factor. Document-literal connectivity (CONST)."
        },
        "verts_on_face": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "shape": ["faces", "local_verts"],
          "description": "Vertex ids of each face — the ragged `face_vertices` values factor (CSR member gather). Document-literal connectivity (CONST)."
        },
        "n_edges_on_cell": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "shape": ["cells"],
          "description": "Valence of each cell (edges per cell) — the ragged `edges_of_cell` offsets factor."
        },
        "edges_on_cell": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "shape": ["cells", "local_edges"],
          "description": "Dense edge ids incident on each cell — the ragged `edges_of_cell` values factor; the INVERSION of the face->edge relation (§5.2)."
        },
        "dc": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "shape": ["edges"],
          "description": "Distance between the cell centers sharing each edge (the DUO primal length), keyed by dense edge id."
        },
        "dv": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "shape": ["edges"],
          "description": "Length of each edge (the DUO dual length), keyed by dense edge id."
        },
        "edge_exists": {
          "type": "state",
          "shape": ["edges"],
          "description": "Materialized edge-membership over the derived `edges` set, assigned algebraically from the CONST connectivity (the index-set-producing aggregate output)."
        },
        "edge_dense_id": {
          "type": "state",
          "shape": ["edges"],
          "description": "Dense integer ids over the derived `edges` set (the array-backend index), assigned from the rank."
        },
        "area_eff": {
          "type": "state",
          "shape": ["cells"],
          "description": "Effective cell area, the downstream geometric sum_product FAQ over edges_of_cell — replaces the imperative per-edge Julia loop."
        }
      },
      "equations": [
        {
          "_comment": "(1)+(2) edge_set: the index-set-producing node referenced by index_sets.edges.from_faq. semiring bool_and_or + distinct:true dedups the unique undirected edges discovered from the face->vertex connectivity; ranges iterate each face f and the vertex pairs (a,b) of that face ({from face_vertices, of [f]}); filter a<b keeps each undirected edge once; key mints the canonical Skolem term skolem(edge,a,b); the `true` body marks existence. Output order is the §5.7 sorted order. This is the literal RFC §7.3 form.",
          "lhs": {
            "op": "index",
            "args": ["edge_exists", "edge"]
          },
          "rhs": {
            "op": "aggregate",
            "id": "edge_set",
            "args": ["faces"],
            "semiring": "bool_and_or",
            "distinct": true,
            "output_idx": ["edge"],
            "ranges": {
              "f": { "from": "faces" },
              "a": { "from": "face_vertices", "of": ["f"] },
              "b": { "from": "face_vertices", "of": ["f"] }
            },
            "filter": { "op": "<", "args": ["a", "b"] },
            "key": {
              "op": "skolem",
              "args": ["edge", "a", "b"]
            },
            "expr": { "op": "true", "args": [] }
          }
        },
        {
          "_comment": "(3) rank: dense integer ids over the derived `edges` set, by position in the sorted distinct sequence (§5.5 / §5.7.3) — what the array backend indexes by.",
          "lhs": {
            "op": "index",
            "args": ["edge_dense_id", "e"]
          },
          "rhs": {
            "op": "aggregate",
            "args": [],
            "semiring": "sum_product",
            "output_idx": ["e"],
            "ranges": { "e": { "from": "edges" } },
            "expr": { "op": "rank", "args": ["edges"] }
          }
        },
        {
          "_comment": "(4)+(5) downstream geometric FAQ: area_eff[i] = 1/4 * Sum_{k in edges_of_cell(i)} dc[e]*dv[e], e = edges_on_cell(i,k). edges_of_cell is the ragged inversion join (§5.2): output index i over cells (dense), contraction k over the per-cell ragged edge set; dc/dv are gathered by the dense edge id. An ordinary sum_product FAQ that consumes the derived `edges` set as a PRIMITIVE index set — the DUO effective area, replacing imperative Julia.",
          "lhs": {
            "op": "aggregate",
            "args": [],
            "output_idx": ["i"],
            "expr": {
              "op": "D",
              "args": [{ "op": "index", "args": ["area_eff", "i"] }],
              "wrt": "t"
            },
            "ranges": { "i": { "from": "cells" } }
          },
          "rhs": {
            "op": "aggregate",
            "args": ["dc", "dv", "edges_on_cell"],
            "semiring": "sum_product",
            "output_idx": ["i"],
            "ranges": {
              "i": { "from": "cells" },
              "k": { "from": "edges_of_cell", "of": ["i"] }
            },
            "expr": {
              "op": "*",
              "args": [
                0.25,
                {
                  "op": "index",
                  "args": ["dc", { "op": "index", "args": ["edges_on_cell", "i", "k"] }]
                },
                {
                  "op": "index",
                  "args": ["dv", { "op": "index", "args": ["edges_on_cell", "i", "k"] }]
                }
              ]
            }
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
